I do not deny that, by daily conver- sation with the Indians, Ι learnt the names of those things which are present to the eyes3 but invisible things, which relate to God and the soul, can only be learnt by conjecture and very long use. When horses, tigers, or armS, are talked of, you will find any of the Abipones a Demosthenes or a Tully: if the question turn on the affections and functions of the mind, and the practice of virtue, they will either give you answers darker than night, or remain silent.
